widgets_values: close-up, age 18, fog, graceful, ethereal, textured skin, photorealistic, gravestones, upper body photo, ruined makeup

-------- INSTRUCTION GUIDE ---------

1. Quick Controls

1.1 ON / OFF Switches
For every module (ie. txt2img, img2img, etc.) there is an ON / OFF switch. Switching this module to OFF means it will not run, and to ON means it will run.

1.2 Seed
Set the seed for the module. Each module has it's own seed. You can copy/paste the seed from one module to another if you want to standardize them, or let them run separately. In order to generate new images, switch the seed from "fixed" to either "increment", "decrement", or "random". I suggest using "increment" so that when you find an image you like, you can switch it to fixed and decrease the value by 1 to lock that image in.

1.3 Steps
Set the step count for the module. The number of steps you should use is dependent on which sampler you are using (ie. Euler, DDIM, DPMPP 2M SDE, etc.). Experiment with both low and high steps. Just remember, the higher the steps, the longer it will take. The goal is to find the lowest amount of steps needed to generate a good image reliably.

1.4 % Base
This is used only in the txt2img module to support splitting the total steps between the base model and the refiner model. If you turn off the refiner model, update your % Base to "1.0" so that the base model runs the full amount of steps.

1.5 Denoise
The Denoising strength is equivalent to how much change you want to see in the resulting image. The higher the value, the more change you will see. This can be both a good thing and a bad thing. With a high denoising strength, you will add detail that may have been missing from your image (ie. skin texture), but run a higher chance of getting mutations. A low denoising strength is great if you want to lock in the existing details without making any real changes.

1.6 Positive / Negative Prompts
Each module has it's own prompts. Feel free to use unique prompts per module, or the same prompt across all 5. The prompts support both the SDXL and SD1.5 methods, which can be changed in the modules corresponding prompt section below.



2. Checkpoint Selection
You have the option of selecting from 1 of 3 checkpoint loaders. Feel free to load whatever checkpoints you want into them. You can then use the modules "Checkpoint Selection" area below to chose which checkpoint will be used for the module.



3. AfterDetailer

This allows you to alter specific portions of an image detected by the Ultralytics models. This includes face detection, hand detection, and person detection. This is basically just inpainting, with the masks drawn for you.

3.1 Face Detailer
Select one of the bbox/face_*.pt models. Personally, I like using the bbox/face_yolov8n_v2.pt model for this.

3.2 Hand Detailer
Select one of the bbox/hand_*.pt models. I'd suggest the bbox/hand_yolov8n.pt model.

3.3 Person Detailer
Select one of the segm/person_*.pt models. I haven't played with this much, so you will need to experiment with which model works best for you.



4. Inpainting

4.1 How? Magic...
Here is something you may not know... If you right click on the Inpaint Image node, you will have an option to "Open in Mask Editor". This Mask Editor gives you the ability to draw your own mask directly on the image, similar to A1111 inpainting. Once you are done drawing your mask, click the "Save to Node" button to commit your mask to the image. This is now the area that will be inpainted!

4.2 How to Load an Image?

4.2.1 The Basic Way
On the Inpaint Image Node, there is a button to "chose file to upload". Once you click that, you will be presented with the standard file explorer where you can select your image.

4.2.2 Copy / Paste
With ComfyUI, there is the concept of the Clipspace, which is essentially like a clipboard, keeping track of all your copies and allowing you to paste them. If you just generated an image that you want to Inpaint, right click on the image and select "Copy (Clipspace)". You can then right click on the Inpaint Image node and select "Paste (Clipspace)".

4.3 Segmentation! More Magic...
If the "Open in Mask Editor" didn't blow your mind, segmentation just might. When you right click on the Inpaint Image node, instead of selecting "Open in Mask Editor", select "Open in SAM Detector". The UI will look similar, but in this case you will only need to put a dot down in a location you want to have detected and then click "Detect". Once you have verified the SAM Detector has auto-masked the right part(s) of the image, you can click "Save to Node" to apply the mask to the image.



5. ControlNet

5.1 ControlNet Preprocessors
Load your image into the preprocessor and then run "Queue Prompt". This will convert your image into a ControlNet input image. I suggest setting the width and height of the image to the same dimensions as the image you are looking to generate.

5.2 ControlNet
Every module has it's own ControlNet section, where you can copy/paste the preprocessed image and select the type of ControlNet you are looking to run. You can also adjust the strength, start percent, and end percent. This ControlNet will apply to the module when generating the output image.

5.2.1 Strength
This is how closely the resulting image will align to the ControlNet image. The higher the value, the more similar the generation is to the ControlNet input

5.2.2 Start Percent
When to start applying the ControlNet in the image generation process. Starting it early means the image will better align to the ControlNet input.

5.2.3 End Percent
When to stop applying the ControlNet in the image generation process.
